Restore America's Estuaries (RAE) created the Inclusive Coast Initiative (ICI)  Workshop Series with regular feedback from participants and partners. RAE selected the topics discussed at workshops with the ICI Working Group, a group of influential professionals with diverse careers in the conservation and restoration community as well as an initial survey sent to early workshop participants. Through working group meetings, we decided on the topics:  


improving equity in grantmaking; 
 rethinking your application process; 
 partners, community, and program design for funders workshops and  
 understanding your community; 
 building partnerships with your community;  
 designing your program for implementors.  



We narrowed these broad topics by examining current research around best practices as well as presentations from knowledgeable guest speakers. At the end of the presentations, we encouraged participants to ask questions of speakers before joining breakout sessions to meet fellow attendees and discuss the topics and how they relate to their own experience. 


From the workshop series we found five key takeaways. The first is that community engagement is a skill and an organizational process. This takeaway includes things like embedding community engagement into every step of the project, attending community events, and ensuring the entire intended audience for a project is reached. The second is to creatively fund multi-benefit projects. This takeaway delves into the idea of expanding the goals of grant programs to include benefits the community needs. The third takeaway is acknowledging history while building a better future. The key to this takeaway is remembering that organizations from the government and from environmental nonprofits have caused harm in communities in the past and acknowledging the hesitation with working with a similar group. Takeaway four is to emphasize learning by providing feedback. Providing feedback to applicants can improve their relationships with funders and improve the quality of their applications for other rounds of that grant program and for other programs. The final takeaway was to reduce barriers for applicants. Some suggestions from that takeaway included having a grant applicant pool to meet match, simplifying application requirements, and minimizing reporting requirements.  


These five key takeaways are the core of the mission we hope reached our audience. From feedback we received at these workshops, we created a new series called the Inclusive Coasts Initiative Communities of Practice (COP’s). The Communities of Practice are a space for people from different organizations to share their struggles and successes with different DEIJ-topics their organizations. To create the COP’s, we created three groups, the Program Managers, Restoration Professionals, and the Community Engagement and Environmental Education group. We then worked with Community of Practice attendees to form a list of topics for discussion and have been working through that list at our sessions since! We look forward to the future of our Inclusive Coasts Initiative and hope to continue to make the coastal restoration field more equitable.   









